# Working in the repo

## Scope discipline
- Do exactly what's asked. If you spot something else worth fixing, mention it — don't silently expand the diff.
- One concern per change. A bug fix and a refactor go in separate commits/PRs.
- Don't reformat files you didn't otherwise touch. Don't rename things "while you're in there."

## Files to never touch without explicit ask
- `package-lock.json` / `yarn.lock` / `pnpm-lock.yaml` — only changes when dependencies change.
- `forge.config.ts`, signing/notarization config, entitlements — confirm first.
- Anything under `build/` related to signing or icons — confirm first.
- CI configuration — confirm first.

## Commits
- Imperative subject, under ~70 chars. Body explains *why* when it isn't obvious.
- One logical change per commit. Don't squash unrelated work together.
- Never `git push --force` to a shared branch. Never `--no-verify` to skip hooks.

## Secrets and credentials
- Nothing secret in source, ever. No API keys, no signing certs, no `.env` contents.
- `.env*` files belong in `.gitignore`. If you find one tracked, stop and flag it.

## When something is broken
- Don't paper over errors with try/catch that swallows them. Either handle the error meaningfully or let it bubble.
- If a test starts failing after your change, fix the cause — don't `.skip` it without saying so loudly.
